%Steps%

[REGION:note]
You should have a copy of **Visual Studio 2013** for Desktop (Preferably Community or Professional Editions) installed before starting this tutorial.
[/REGION]

During this step, you will create a starting point for your First Person Shooter (FPS) game by using Unreal Engine 4's Project Browser.

1.	Open **Unreal Engine** from the Launcher. The [](Engine/Basics/Projects/Browser) will appear.

1.	Click on the **New Project** tab and then select the **Blueprint** tab.

1.	Select the **Blank** project.

1.	Name the project "FPSProject". Make sure **No Starter Content** is set.
	
	![](UnrealPrjBrowser.png)

	[REGION:warning]
	Some of the code samples in this tutorial will need to be updated if you name your project differently.
	[/REGION]

1.	Click the **Create Project** button.

1.	Your project is now open in Unreal Editor. Click the **Play** button in the Level Editor to move around the level. Use the WASD keys to move and use the mouse to aim your camera.

	![](ClickPlayButton.png)

1.	Click the **Stop** button in the Level Editor to exit Play in Editor (PIE) mode.

	![](ClickStopButton.png)

1.	Create a Maps folder within the Content folder.

	![](MapsFolder.png)

1.	In the **File** menu, select **Save as...** to save your level as "FPSMap" within the Maps folder.

	![](SaveLevelAs.png)

1.	In the **Edit** menu, click on **Project Settings**.

1.	Under the **Project** heading on the left side of the **Project Settings** tab, click on **Maps & Modes**.

1.	Select **FPSMap** as the **Editor Startup Map** using the dropdown menu.

	![](EditorDefaultMap.png)

	[REGION:note]
	From now on, the editor will automatically load FPSMap as the default map.
	[/REGION]

1.	Close the **Project Settings** menu.

